{"author":{"id":"eaa688ea0d726436b1ece55a8b9d1b531ea04439eb81761f069a85729bf89eab"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1699534305,"nonce":"TvV6J5FBFWweXiHXJV2f2orKufo=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s5rg2fj","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/5585#issuecomment-1803773923"},"message":"Hey @bernt-matthias \n\nI've tried this before by the suggestion of @astrovsky01 over a zoom call, but to no avail. The problem seems to stem from the reticulate package itself, which checks for a conda environment by looking for the existence of `/usr/local/conda-meta`. \n\nBut, from what I understand about biocontainers (**and do correct me if I'm wrong!**), the conda environment is built outside of the container, and then copied in, but without conda inside. \n\nSo when reticulate tries to find conda/mamba it fails.\n\nThe current workaround I have found is to mask the function that detects conda, and then everything seems to work:\n\n    library(reticulate)\n    assignInNamespace(\"is_conda_python\", function(x){ return(FALSE) }, ns=\"reticulate\")\n    reticulate:::use_python(\"/usr/local/bin/python\")   ## failed on normalizePath error previously\n\nThis is a horrible hack, but it works.\n\nBetween biocontainers and reticulate, I'm not actually sure whose  problem this is. I believe reticulate is not incorrect in detecting a conda installation from the conda-meta directory.","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1699534362,"nonce":"/yQQKw2Mh3fsZAcFT3PB4PQ3zzE=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lALOAW4Y0s5rg2fjzjqMpUI"},"target":"a48824a995243d9642f3cfe7c5b203f5e53eb9aa4cb697f7adcdd1e79e902324","message":"Hey @bernt-matthias \n\nI've tried this before by the suggestion of @astrovsky01 over a zoom call, but to no avail. The problem seems to stem from the reticulate package itself, which checks for a conda environment by looking for the existence of `/usr/local/conda-meta`. \n\nBut, from what I understand about biocontainers (**and do correct me if I'm wrong!**), the conda environment is built outside of the container, and then copied into the docker, but without conda inside.  (I looked at the docker history command, and it seems that it copies a mulled directory).\n\nSo when reticulate tries to find conda/mamba it fails.\n\nThe current workaround I have found is to mask the function that detects conda, and then everything seems to work:\n\n    library(reticulate)\n    assignInNamespace(\"is_conda_python\", function(x){ return(FALSE) }, ns=\"reticulate\")\n    reticulate:::use_python(\"/usr/local/bin/python\")   ## failed on normalizePath error previously\n\nThis is a horrible hack, but it works.\n\nBetween biocontainers and reticulate, I'm not actually sure whose  problem this is. I believe reticulate is not incorrect in detecting a conda installation from the conda-meta directory.","files":null}]}